Black's knight is well placed on g4.

Thank goodness for my knight.  Thereby, black abandons his knight attack, apparently planning to put his dsB and rooks on the d file.  Perhaps he also didn't like my queen on d3.
Thank goodness for my knight.  Thereby, black abandons his knight attack, apparently planning to put his dsB and rooks on the d file.  Perhaps he also didn't like my queen on d3.

Bd6 or Rfe8 were expected, though this is much the same, also preventing my plan of Qg5.  Black is planning Rxd5 and Bd4, which would pin the white queen and king, and is attacking the rook on a1.  Black can only move Bd4 by first taking with Rxd5, so might double his rooks on the d file or move Qd3.  However, my rook is a good defense for his queen.  My queen is still unprotected, but the rook on a1 must be moved.  I want to get free and go after his pawns.  Rad1 and Qd3 should put me in a better position.
